    <node id="&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: No, but does anybody come to you and say, 'Well, actually, I've really come here because I don't have to do the Welsh bac'?&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: The honest answer is it's one of the first questions that people always ask. But, as I've said, as a parent, I've been to open evenings and other open evenings. It's generally a question that people ask, 'Do I have to do the Welsh bac?' It does come across not just in our open evenings, but in other open evenings that I've been to. It is always a question that people ask me. They do want to know that, and it's usually, as I said, one of the first questions that they ask.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: And is that the parents asking the question or the pupil?&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: It's a combination. But, honest answer, I would say parents, a lot of the time, but the learners usually—as I said—have sometimes had not the best experience pre 16 and that's why they ask the question straight away." />
    <node id="ate.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Did you have a supplementary, Siân?&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Yes. You didn't mention Cardiff University there.&#10;Speaker: Kay Martin&#10;Content: Cardiff University—yes. My daughter's example—that was Cardiff University. So, they do, especially now it's graded at level 3. Then they do accept it. A great number of our learners get into Cardiff using the Welsh baccalaureate, but would their admissions tutors prefer four A-levels? Absolutely.&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: Could I jump in there? I've got to jump in there as, from the institution I'm in, we've had a long track record of getting learners into top universities. About 20 per cent of our learners go to Russell Group universities, and there is no doubt—in certainly 50 per cent of those, they do not value the Welsh bac. But if they do offer an option with the Welsh bac, they say it is on top of three A2-level grades. So, obviously, we've had that track record. I think the Seren programme that's been put in by the" />
    <node id="1. Perception of repetition: The perception among learners that the Welsh Baccalaureate experience in school is repetitive with college coursework can be attributed to the fact that many students have already been exposed to similar content and skills during their Welsh Bac experience at the school level. This redundancy can lead to a lack of motivation and engagement, particularly for students transitioning from Level 1 to Level 2.&#10;&#10;2. Adoption by universities: The adoption of the Welsh Baccalaureate by universities and admissions tutors impacts its value for university applications, especially for competitive programs like dentistry or those offered by Oxbridge or high-level Russell Group universities. Although the Welsh Baccalaureate is technically universally adopted by universities, not all admissions tutors in every university consider it equally valuable. Some may prefer four A-levels over a combination of A-levels and the Welsh Baccalaureate, particularly for subjects like dentistry and those within the Seren network.&#10;&#10;This inconsistency in adoption by universities and admissions tutors can lead to confusion among students regarding the true value of the Welsh Baccalaureate for their university applications, especially when pursuing competitive programs or applying to prestigious institutions." />
    <node id=", they're coming to us having been through a Welsh bac experience at school, and therefore many of the learners feel that there's repeating going on then—'Oh, we've done this at school already. Why are we doing it again at college?' So, I think that's a problem for us as well.&#10;Speaker: Kay Martin&#10;Content: Many have experienced a paper-based exercise rather than a real activity. So, at level 1 and level 2, it's not what we would call a crowd puller in colleges, but at level 3 it's more, especially for A-levels, because it can help them get into university, but even for the more able and talented—we were discussing this, weren't we? We have learners who do four A-levels, but they don't do the Welsh baccalaureate because they're part of the Seren network, and they are going to be applying for Oxbridge or high-level Russell Group universities. So, the Welsh bac, although it's technically universally adopted by universities, it isn't adopted by every admissions tutor in every university. So, to get into some areas, like dentistry, for example, and some of the other Seren-type activities" />
    <node id=" every admissions tutor in every university. So, to get into some areas, like dentistry, for example, and some of the other Seren-type activities, four A-levels is better. But in most colleges that have A-level students it's almost compulsory to do the Welsh bac as well, but normally that would be three A-levels and the Welsh bac—normally.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Okay. And then ColegauCymru say that, increasingly, the Welsh bac is not being offered at post-16 national and foundation level. So, are the different levels of the Welsh bac valued differently by further education professionals?&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: Yes.&#10;Speaker: Kay Martin&#10;Content: Yes.&#10;Speaker: Dafydd Evans&#10;Content: Yes.&#10;Speaker: Dr Rachel Bowen&#10;Content: Yes.&#10;Speaker: Ed Evans&#10;Content: Yes.&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: I think we've got to bear in mind when the students come to us—certainly when they're level 1, level 2 learners—that a number of them have come from school and probably not done as" />
    <node id=" of three A2-level grades. So, obviously, we've had that track record. I think the Seren programme that's been put in by the Welsh Government is looking to increase the numbers applying to top universities and top courses, but you look through the range, particularly in science, technology, engineering and mathematics subjects as well, across a number and range of universities, the Welsh bac is always added as the additional one. So, bear in mind, then, that Welsh students are fighting for places against Scottish, Northern Irish and, potentially, English students who are studying three subjects, whereas our Welsh students potentially could be doing three A2s, three A-level subjects plus the Welsh bac. And, as we talked about earlier on, the Welsh bac has evolved into quite a rigorous, you could say complicated, qualification, which puts added pressure on a learner in year 2 when they're trying to get possibly three A* grades. So, I think we need to consider that. In relation to the first answer, it is variable, and the admissions tutors throughout a lot of universities will make different decisions, and also make the decision dependent on whether it's a facilitating subject or an enabling subject, which the Russell Group report indicates about" />
    <node id=" for university—but does it help my health and social care people become more skilled and employable? No, it doesn't.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Thank you.&#10;Speaker: Dr Rachel Bowen&#10;Content: And this, ultimately, has to be about what's in the best interests of learners, and a one-size-fits-all approach isn't going to work.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Thank you. Is there a difference in how the Welsh bac is valued by learners at the different levels that it is studied? ColegauCymru said that learners may have had a negative experience of the Welsh bac in previous study.&#10;Speaker: Dafydd Evans&#10;Content: That's been a new dimension lately, I think, in that, when the Welsh bac first hit FE, we were leading the way—&#10;Speaker: Kay Martin&#10;Content: Great advocates.&#10;Speaker: Dafydd Evans&#10;Content: —and great advocates. By now, of course, they're coming to us having been through a Welsh bac experience at school, and therefore many of the learners feel that there's repeating going on then—" />
    <node id=" have really worked hard to contextualise the Welsh bac within the vocational area, within the A-level subjects that the learners are doing, are finding it very rewarding. So, there are some very positive things coming out there. I think what we're suggesting is there may be even better ways of doing it and better ways of explaining to people what it's about.&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: On this point about the skills being developed, I think that's debatable if all the skills that are supposed to be developed in the Welsh bac are being developed, and that's why I think there's a need to relook at it to make sure those skills are being developed fully. But I will go back to the point that I think a comparable qualification is comparable as long as it achieves the right outcome for that particular learner. If you force a learner to do something that is not necessarily going to achieve the outcome that they require in their future, is it the right thing to be doing for that learner? That's what my concern is.&#10;Speaker: Dr Rachel Bowen&#10;Content: I think the baccalaureate approach is best at producing independent, inquiry-based learners who have the skills to look" />
    <node id="'ve potentially hopefully progressed to level 3. But I think it's questionable, certainly at national and foundation. And the important point that Dafydd raised was that there's a lot of repetition there in school, pre 16 to post 16 at those levels as well. So, learners don't come in banging at the door saying, 'We want to do the Welsh bac because it's exactly the same or very similar to what we did when we were in school.' They want to see some difference, they want to see some progress, and that's not necessarily the case in the foundation and national levels.&#10;Speaker: Dr Rachel Bowen&#10;Content: And we know that delivery in schools is of variable quality, so obviously that impacts on how learners have experienced it and perhaps how they view it when they get to FE college.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Okay. A question, then, just to ColegauCymru: to what extent do you believe that universities in the main understand the value of the Welsh bac?&#10;Speaker: Kay Martin&#10;Content: Well, we don't think they do, really, especially the experience we have with some of our learners to go to Russell Group universities. They" />
    <node id="1. In Swansea, all students are required to participate in the Welsh Baccalaureate, regardless of whether they are doing A-levels or vocational qualifications.&#10;2. In Cardiff and the Vale, only students who are part of the Seren network (an initiative for encouraging able and talented young people to consider higher education) are required to participate in the Welsh Baccalaureate.&#10;3. In a particular college, all students, including those doing four A-levels, must participate in the Welsh Baccalaureate. This is different from the approach taken in other regions and institutions. The speakers do not explicitly discuss the reasons for these differences in policy, but they suggest that the implementation of 'contextualising the curriculum' may vary depending on the specific challenges and opportunities faced by each institution or region." />
    <node id=" in a structured way, not an ad-hoc way, which is just a friend turning up to talk about something, a structured way—. We have a programme under way at the moment called 'contextualising the curriculum' in the sector that we hope to roll out. Now, if that was rolled out across the board—I'm not saying that it makes it easier for teachers in particular, but they are going to struggle to deliver some of these commercial and world-skilled, global areas, because it's not their bag. So, bring in some experts, bring in some business, raise the profile, and I think then, possibly, you'll start to get parents thinking, 'Actually, there is something more to this than just the academic bit.'&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: Okay. I think all my other points have been answered, Chair. Thank you.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay. Can I just ask—? You've all got slightly different policies; they don't have to do it in Swansea, in Cardiff and the Vale, they do unless they're in the Seren network, and in your college, everybody does it, even if they're doing four A-" />
    <node id=" an overemphasis, by us all, on A-levels—.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Thank you. We've got some questions now from Dawn Bowden.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: Thank you, Chair. A lot of this has been covered, actually, but just on those final points there, I'm wondering whether you think that introducing a specialist teacher-training qualification to deliver the Welsh bac would actually help in some way in improving its status and perception and so on. What do you think about that?&#10;Speaker: Dafydd Evans&#10;Content: I'm not assured in terms of—yes, training is required regarding the Welsh bac, but where we are seeing it more successfully is where vocational lecturers have actually taken it on board. When we were bringing lecturers from outside—'Welsh bac specialists' in inverted commas—it was not working well. It has started to work well when our sports lecturers have taken the Welsh bac on board and have put it in the context of the sports curriculum. Therefore, no, I think that if it's going to be a success, it's got to be contextualised, and for" />
    <node id=" context of the sports curriculum. Therefore, no, I think that if it's going to be a success, it's got to be contextualised, and for the vocational lecturers to do that, and we've invested heavily in training those vocational lecturers to understand how to deliver the Welsh bac and get positive outcomes of the Welsh bac—. It's been an intensive staff development process.&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: And I think you've got to bear in mind that the number of the skills and the number of challenges that are done within the Welsh bac are done very similarly within the vocational qualification as well. So, a number of those staff have already got those skills and they're undertaking that. I suppose when it comes to the word 'credibility' used in terms of the qualification, yes, I'm sure it would raise that focus on it, but ultimately, it's taking away from the fact that we have got staff who've got those skills and they're developing them within other elements of the vocational qualifications they're doing. Something we were talking about earlier on is the fact is that, sometimes, that work is being repeated twice, because of the nature of the qualification.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM" />
    <node id="It is quite questionable for level 1 and 2 learners to effectively benefit from resitting GCSE exams and adding a Welsh Baccalaureate qualification. The pressure on these students is already high due to their resits in English and maths, and the added volume of work from the Welsh baccalaureate can increase this pressure further. This can be counterproductive, as the primary goal for bringing such learners in at that level should be building their confidence and skills, which might be better served through a more focused curriculum without the additional burden of the Welsh Baccalaureate. Furthermore, there is uncertainty about whether all the intended skills developed through the Welsh baccalaureate are indeed being fully realized by learners. The benefits of the Welsh Baccalaureate may be better experienced at Level 3, once students have built a stronger foundation and academic capacity to handle its demands." />
    <node id=" the problems that we have is that we have a number of children coming in to the colleges, and they need to resit their GCSEs—in maths, English and Welsh. It's a valid priority for the Welsh Government for everyone to get a C grade in the core subjects. But that eats into the time that we have to teach young people. And so there's no room for everything in the curriculum somehow—no room in the funding or also in terms of the time and the capacity of the learner to be able to do that number of qualifications. So, the priorities, I think, across the sector—. We've given priority to GCSE resits rather than doing the Welsh bac at present. So, at levels 1 and 2, there are fewer and fewer doing 1 and 2 in the baccalaureate because they're resitting their GCSEs, and there is much more use of the Welsh bac at level 3, and A-level, and vocational level 3.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Okay. Thank you.&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: Can I just add to that? I think, again, there's a misconception. The Welsh b" />
    <node id=" students come to us—certainly when they're level 1, level 2 learners—that a number of them have come from school and probably not done as well as they'd hoped at their GCSEs. Okay, they've come to us, they're trying to build themselves back up, build their skills back up, and adding another qualification on top, adding the Welsh bac on top, whether that's foundation or national, on top of what they have to do, which is a programme they've come and decided to do—think of the pressure that increases upon them. Plus the fact is that they are resitting; they're probably having to resit GCSE English and maths as well. That's a huge volume of work for a learner who's probably come from a low base to begin with and who hasn't achieved what they wanted to. The whole idea when we bring them in at that level is that we want to build their confidence, build them up and, hopefully, eventually they will go to the stage where maybe the Welsh bac will be beneficial to them, when they've potentially hopefully progressed to level 3. But I think it's questionable, certainly at national and foundation. And the important point that Dafydd raised was" />
    <node id="1. Softer skills can be developed through programs that offer skill-building opportunities without requiring a formal qualification. This approach is supported by Nick Brazil, who mentioned that their organization offers such programs, which have proven effective in developing the necessary skills among learners (Content: &quot;We run programmes as well. They're not qualifications, but they offer the opportunity to develop those softer skills.&quot;).&#10;2. The transcript suggests that some young people may be seeking out alternative education settings with more flexibility and opportunities for skill development tailored to their needs. Lynne Neagle AM raised a question about young people from the Swansea area who might choose alternative education providers for this reason (Content: &quot;Are you aware, then, of any young people who are coming to you from the Swansea area because they've got that flexibility, which they may not have in one of the local schools?&quot;).&#10;3. The Welsh Baccalaureate approach is valued for its ability to create independent and inquiry-based learners with strong skills, even if it might not be optimal for all learners at specific levels. Dawn Bowden AM and Rachel Bowen both highlighted the positive aspects of the baccalaureate approach (Content: &quot;I think the baccalaureate approach is best at producing independent, inquiry-based learners who have the skills to look&quot;). However, there are concerns about fitting it into a specific qualification format and potentially losing some of its benefits.&#10;4. The experiences of pre-16 students with qualifications may not always accurately reflect their skill levels. Suzy Davies AM raised a concern that sometimes young people present pieces of paper indicating they have certain skills, but in practice, they do not demonstrate those skills (Content: &quot;at pre 16, would it be fair to say that there have been occasions when people have come presenting those pieces of paper but actually show none of the skills that they were supposed to have?&quot;). This highlights the need for alternative methods of skill development and assessment beyond formal qualifications." />
    <node id=" Davies AM&#10;Content: That's great. Thank you.&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: Can I just add something to that? I think Ed's just said about the softer skills. Do the softer skills have to be developed through qualification? I think Kay mentioned a programme earlier on within her college. We run programmes as well. They're not qualifications, but they offer the opportunity to develop those softer skills. So, I think we're all in agreement about the development of the skills, but does it need to be through a qualification?&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: And you've said that you make the decision in the best interests of the learner. Are you aware, then, of any young people who are coming to you from the Swansea area because they've got that flexibility, which they may not have in one of the local schools?&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: As I said, in terms of our offer, we offer a range in the curriculum. We're not going out there saying, 'Come to us for this particular reason.'&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: No, but does anybody come to you and say, 'Well, actually, I've really come" />
    <node id=" more greatly, which I accept. Are you worried at all, though, that some of the more able and talented STEM students, in particular—who are needed in your sector, after all—might be deterred from doing those four A-levels because of the bac, because, presumably, you need a mix of these talents? You talked about the more able and talented vocational learners, but also you have more able and talented academic learners—presumably you need them all.&#10;Speaker: Ed Evans&#10;Content: We do. There's a big range, and some really high achievers coming into the sector as well. So, it is about that mix. I think the discussion that I've had with our employers has been around the academic side of things, if you like. The qualifications are well catered for. So, it's almost a given somebody's been through that route. What isn't there is some of those softer skills, but also some—. I was almost going to call commercial skills 'soft' there—.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Call them 'commercial'.&#10;Speaker: Ed Evans&#10;Content: Commercial skills are hard skills, which are very, very difficult to come by. So, the" />
    <node id=" Rachel Bowen&#10;Content: I think the baccalaureate approach is best at producing independent, inquiry-based learners who have the skills to look to teachers not as sources of information but just for guidance. That whole sort of approach about creating inquisitive young people with the skills that we've discussed, that's a real positive. The chances are that we've lost some of that by trying to fit it into being a specific qualification. The approach is a positive one.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Suzy, you had a supplementary.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Yes, to both Rachel Bowen and Nick Brazil, if you don't mind. Both of you mentioned this is about skills and a piece of paper that demonstrates that you have these skills. At pre 16, would it be fair to say that there have been occasions when people have come presenting those pieces of paper but actually show none of the skills that they were supposed to have? The reason I'm asking this question, having had children who've gone through the process myself, is that in some schools, and I'm not saying all, doing the bac is something that everybody does in the last four weeks of term, and that" />
    <node id="Based on the statements made by Kay Martin from ColegauCymru, it appears that there is a perception that Russell Group universities do not fully understand or value the Welsh Baccalaureate. This conclusion is drawn from the experiences of learners attempting to gain admission to these universities. The statement suggests that some admissions tutors within Russell Group universities may prefer four A-levels over a combination of A-levels and the Welsh Baccalaureate, particularly for competitive programs like dentistry or subjects within the Seren network. This inconsistency in adoption can lead to confusion among students regarding the true value of the Welsh Baccalaureate for their university applications, especially when pursuing competitive programs or applying to prestigious institutions." />
    <node id="1. The Welsh Baccalaureate is designed to develop a range of skills, including employability skills, which can help learners become more well-rounded and useful job candidates. However, there are concerns that the focus on outcomes and the qualification aspect has overshadowed the initial vision of developing skills through this program.&#10;&#10;2. There is a perception among some students that the Welsh Baccalaureate covers content and skills redundant with their college coursework, leading to demotivation and disengagement. This issue might be particularly prominent for learners transitioning from Level 1 to Level 2.&#10;&#10;3. The adoption of the Welsh Baccalaureate by universities and admissions tutors can impact its value for university applications, especially for competitive programs or prestigious institutions. Although it is universally adopted, not all admissions tutors consider it equally valuable, which can create confusion among students.&#10;&#10;4. Some colleges and regions have implemented unique policies regarding the Welsh Baccalaureate, such as requiring all students to participate regardless of their qualifications. These differences in policy might be due to variations in contextualizing the curriculum depending on specific challenges and opportunities faced by each institution or region.&#10;&#10;5. To ensure that learners develop the intended skills through the Welsh Baccalaureate, there is a need to reassess and refocus on its original vision of emphasizing skill development rather than solely outcomes. Additionally, tailoring the program to meet individual learner needs and aligning it with industry requirements can enhance its value in preparing students for employment." />
    <node id=" think that is a very good question, but I will go back to Ed's point, which I think was a very important point, which is that the initial vision for the Welsh bac—I think when we go back a number of years—was a really good, good vision for the Welsh bac. It was going to be an overarching qualification that developed these skills, and certainly employability skills, and I think it's lost its way since then. It's become a qualification and all the realms around becoming a qualification, and it's become very much focused on outcomes rather than necessarily skills. And that's what happens, unfortunately. But I think what Ed said is absolutely right: if you get the engagement of the employers—. But you've got to listen to what Kay said as well: there are programmes already out there. So, why are we focusing one way when there are already programmes that work extremely well? I will go to the enhanced programmes, enhanced engineering and programmes that we are running within our college and that I know run in other colleges, which are much, much more focused on skills, much more focused in linking with industry, and they work extremely well. The actual progress of learners into employment is happening. So, I think the question is" />
    <node id="1. Involve employers in the review process of the Welsh Baccalaureate: Dafydd Evans suggests that involving employers in the review of the qualification can help emphasize employability and entrepreneurial skills within the program. By giving employers a sense of ownership in the creation and design of the qualification, they are more likely to understand and value its purpose and objectives.&#10;&#10;2. Encourage direct communication between educational institutions and employers: Strengthening the relationship between schools, colleges, and local businesses can help bridge the gap in understanding. This could involve organizing workshops, job fairs, or internship programs that provide students with hands-on experience and expose employers to the skills developed through the Welsh Baccalaureate.&#10;&#10;3. Tailor the Welsh Baccalaureate curriculum to meet industry requirements: By ensuring that the program aligns with the needs of the local job market, it increases the likelihood that employers will recognize its value. This may involve updating course content, incorporating new technologies, or promoting skills that are in high demand within specific industries.&#10;&#10;4. Create resources and materials explaining the Welsh Baccalaureate's benefits: Developing informational brochures, websites, or videos targeted at employers can help clarify the objectives and advantages of the program. These materials should highlight how the Welsh Baccalaureate prepares students for employment by fostering a range of skills relevant to the modern workforce.&#10;&#10;5. Encourage industry leaders to advocate for the Welsh Baccalaureate: By having prominent business figures or trade organizations endorse the program, employers may be more inclined to recognize its value. This could involve organizing public events, conferences, or campaigns that promote the benefits of the Welsh Baccalaureate and its relevance to the job market.&#10;&#10;Based on the conversation, it appears that Dafydd Evans is primarily responsible for making efforts to persuade employers of the Welsh Baccalaureate's worthiness. However, collective action from various stakeholders, including educators, policymakers, and industry leaders, can contribute significantly to enhancing employers' understanding and appreciation of the program." />
    <node id=" bac, and whose work is it to try to persuade employers that it is worth while, if you feel that it is worth while, of course?&#10;Speaker: Dafydd Evans&#10;Content: I think we need to review the qualification, and I think the voice of employers should be a key part of that review, so that employability skills and entrepreneurial skills have more of a role within that qualification. And I think that rather than it being done by the colleges or by a qualifications board, I think the employers—. And the only way we'll get employer buy-in is that if they feel ownership of what's being done. Because I think that's what the vision was for the Welsh baccalaureate—that it was going to improve skills for employment. But, somehow or other we've lost our way. The aim is an excellent one, but I think we've lost our way in terms of what we do present at the end of the day, and I think having more input from employers would be a great help.&#10;Speaker: Ed Evans&#10;Content: I will carry on in English, if that's okay.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Yes, it" />
    <node id="1. Lack of clarity in title: The title &quot;Welsh Baccalaureate&quot; does not clearly convey its purpose or objectives, which can lead to confusion among stakeholders such as employers, parents, and young people. A more descriptive title, like &quot;Skills Challenge Certificate,&quot; might be easier for them to understand and appreciate its value.&#10;&#10;2. Inadequate understanding by employers: There is a perception that many employers do not fully comprehend the objectives or value of the Welsh Baccalaureate. This issue could be more pronounced among small and microbusinesses, as they may have limited resources to stay updated on educational policy developments and changes in Wales.&#10;&#10;3. Size-based disparity in understanding: The challenge in communicating the value and objectives of the Welsh Baccalaureate varies depending on the size of the employer. Larger employers with dedicated HR personnel might be more aware of policy developments and education evolution, while small and microbusinesses are often too focused on their core operations to engage or understand the Welsh Baccalaureate fully.&#10;&#10;4. Limited awareness among parents and young people: The lack of understanding about the Welsh Baccalaureate extends to parents and young people themselves. This can be a significant challenge, as they may not appreciate its benefits in developing essential skills or preparing for higher education or employment opportunities.&#10;&#10;5. Addressing these challenges: To improve communication about the Welsh Baccalaureate's value and objectives, there is a need to adopt more effective marketing strategies that cater specifically to different stakeholder groups. This may involve creating tailored resources for employers, especially small and microbusinesses, as well as providing clearer information for parents and young people. Additionally, it would be helpful if educational institutions regularly engaged with these stakeholders to address their concerns and promote better understanding of the Welsh Baccalaureate's objectives and benefits." />
    <node id=" I don't think that even the title of the Welsh bac is helpful, because it doesn't say what's happening in the tin. So, I think the skills challenge certificate is a better title, and is something that people understand a lot better than the Welsh bac. So, no, I don't think that employers understand the value or what we're trying to achieve through the Welsh bac at present.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Which is a big problem.&#10;Speaker: Dafydd Evans&#10;Content: Yes, it's a huge problem, but not only to employers, but also to parents and young people, of course.&#10;Speaker: Dr Rachel Bowen&#10;Content: And I think that that varies by size of employer as well. That, certainly, where there are larger employers, who've got people who are able to follow policy developments across the education spectrum, they may have more capacity to follow changes, get up to date with how Welsh education is evolving. But we know that most employers in Wales are small or microbusinesses. And while there are lots of small engaged employers who have taken an interest and do understand, the vast majority are more focused on getting on with the" />
    <node id="1. Incorporating more employer input in the review of the Welsh Baccalaureate qualification can help improve its focus on employability and entrepreneurial skills by ensuring that the program aligns with industry requirements and promotes relevant skill development. Employers have firsthand knowledge of what competencies are needed in the workforce, allowing them to provide valuable insights into updating course content, incorporating new technologies, and promoting high-demand skills within specific industries. This collaboration can lead to a more effective and practical curriculum that better prepares students for employment opportunities.&#10;&#10;2. Employer buy-in is crucial for the success of this initiative because it ensures their understanding and recognition of the Welsh Baccalaureate's value. By giving employers a sense of ownership in the creation and design of the qualification, they are more likely to appreciate its objectives and purpose. This support can translate into various positive outcomes, such as increased willingness to hire students with this credential, providing internship opportunities, or offering guidance on industry-specific skills development. Ultimately, employer buy-in is essential in creating a strong connection between education and the job market, fostering an environment where students are better prepared for employment and career success." />
    <node id="1. Some employers in the sector find that STEM students lack &quot;softer skills&quot; and &quot;commercial skills,&quot; which they consider to be hard skills. These skills are not always provided by professional qualifications and are necessary for success in the industry.&#10;2. The Welsh Baccalaureate is seen as a way to develop these skills, particularly for students who come from a less academic background. It provides challenges that test their abilities and exposes them to industry knowledge.&#10;3. There is concern that the rigorous nature of the Welsh Baccalaureate might deter more able and talented STEM students from pursuing four A-levels, as they are an essential part of the sector's workforce.&#10;4. The lack of understanding among employers about the Welsh Baccalaureate and its benefits, along with the pressure it puts on learners in terms of bureaucracy and workload, has raised questions about whether it truly develops the skills that employers require.&#10;5. Employers prioritize the main qualifications relevant to their industry, such as engineering qualifications for engineers. While they want well-rounded employees, they might not fully understand or value the Welsh Baccalaureate as a means of achieving this goal." />
    <node id="businesses. And while there are lots of small engaged employers who have taken an interest and do understand, the vast majority are more focused on getting on with the day-to-day running of the business. And that means it's quite a challenge to understand what is the Welsh bac, what does it offer. And, certainly, when that's evolved over the past few years and there have been changes, it would have been quite difficult to keep up to date with those, I imagine.&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: Could I add to that? As do many of my colleagues within the colleges, we have a number of employer boards, which we regularly meet with—employers—and I cannot think back as to how many employers say to us, 'That is what we require—the Welsh bac—to come and work within our industry.' Most of what they are questioning is the level of professional qualifications and the quality of skills within those professional sectors. Not many of them have indicated that the Welsh bac is providing the skills that they require. I think many of them believe in the vision that was set out for the Welsh bac initially, but the Welsh bac has turned into quite a rigorous, some" />
