    <node id=" Thank you.&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: Can I just add to that? I think, again, there's a misconception. The Welsh bac is a combination of qualifications; it's not just one qualification—it's a combination. So, to develop the employability skills obviously is a key part, and developing the skills for employment is a key part. But when you are focused, if you are a learner, on developing or achieving certain qualifications to make up the Welsh bac—for example, resits, your main qualification, plus your work for the Welsh bac, which is the skills challenge certificate as well—that's a huge amount of work. And, obviously, when you're trying to achieve outcomes—and we all get funded on the outcomes—that becomes the priority, and sometimes then we lose the focus on the skills, which are ultimately what were supposed to be part of the development for employability. So, I think people lose the fact that the Welsh bac is a combination of things. And I think it was interesting, the comment that was made about the Duke of Edinburgh—I thought that's something that we need to think about.&#10;Speaker: Kay Martin&#10;Content: If I could just say as" />
    <node id="The Welsh Baccalaureate (Welsh bac) is being undermined by some schools completing it in the last four weeks of term. This rushed approach results in learners not fully developing the desired independent skills, which defeats the purpose of the program. The perceived value of the Welsh bac is also affected by the variable models and approaches to teaching it, leading to inconsistencies in skill development. Some schools prioritize the Welsh bac as a requirement for admission, but its value depends on the institution and subjects being studied. There are concerns that not all intended skills developed through the Welsh bac are being fully realized by learners, particularly at Level 1 and 2 where the primary goal should be building confidence and skills with a more focused curriculum. However, there is evidence that when taught effectively, the Welsh bac can be beneficial and rewarding for learners, helping them develop valuable skills. The interviewees seem to agree that a more consistent approach to teaching the Welsh bac is needed to ensure its value and effectiveness in developing independent skills among learners." />
    <node id=" that in some schools, and I'm not saying all, doing the bac is something that everybody does in the last four weeks of term, and that undermines the whole idea of the bac anyway. It's just not fair on the learners or the people teaching the bac. Is that a fair observation?&#10;Speaker: Dr Rachel Bowen&#10;Content: I think it's perfectly possible for learners to reach FE college having attained the Welsh bac under the process that you've described, and without necessarily having gone through the holistic inquiry-based independent skills that we would want to see.&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: Yes, and at interview process or during an interview, or in the first week, you can see that they haven't developed those skills, and I think it is down to the variable models that have been put in place. There are lots of different models, and if you put, as I said, the model that you've described in place, there is no way, in that period of time, you're going to develop those skills. But that indicates, again, the value that people are putting on the qualification, if they are squeezing it into three or four weeks of term.&#10;Speaker: Suzy" />
    <node id=" maybe, but that's what it should do.&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: Right. And those skills that are learnt in the Welsh bac, can they be learnt in any of the other qualifications? Because I know that Cambridge university said to us they thought, in the four A-levels that they asked for, that those skills were there.&#10;Speaker: Kay Martin&#10;Content: It probably depends on the subjects that people are studying and the combination of subjects and the institution. Generally, in college, even if they're doing A-levels, they go out on some community projects or work-related education, without the Welsh bac—even if they're not doing that. So, it does depend on the subject, I think.&#10;Speaker: Dafydd Evans&#10;Content: I think there's a real danger of us perhaps becoming overly critical here as well of the Welsh bac in terms of—I don't think it's perfect by a long way, however, learners are getting some value out of that process. Certain learners in departments where they have really worked hard to contextualise the Welsh bac within the vocational area, within the A-level subjects that the learners are doing, are finding it" />
    <node id="1. Dafydd Evans believes that incorporating more employer input in the review of the Welsh Baccalaureate qualification can help improve its focus on employability and entrepreneurial skills. He suggests this be done by giving employers a sense of ownership in the creation and design of the qualification, which would lead to better alignment with industry requirements and promote relevant skill development. Employer buy-in is crucial for the success of this initiative, as it ensures their understanding and recognition of the Welsh Baccalaureate's value.&#10;&#10;2. Dafydd Evans also recommends involving employers in the review process of the Welsh Baccalaureate to emphasize employability and entrepreneurial skills within the program. Strengthening the relationship between schools, colleges, and local businesses can help bridge the gap in understanding through workshops, job fairs, or internship programs. Tailoring the Welsh Baccalaureate curriculum to meet industry requirements, creating resources and materials explaining its benefits, and encouraging industry leaders to advocate for the program can also contribute significantly to enhancing employers' understanding and appreciation of the program.&#10;&#10;3. Dafydd Evans acknowledges that there have been negative experiences with the Welsh Baccalaureate, particularly among level 1 and 2 learners who may already be struggling with English and maths resits. He suggests that a more focused curriculum without the additional burden of the Welsh Baccalaureate might better serve these students at lower levels, while reserving its benefits for those at Level 3 with stronger academic foundations." />
    <node id="1. Reduced exposure to modern foreign languages: Prioritizing the Welsh Baccalaureate over modern foreign languages in sixth forms may result in fewer students studying these languages, reducing their exposure to different cultures and limiting their language skills. This could be disadvantageous when seeking employment opportunities that require knowledge of multiple languages.&#10;2. Limited understanding of global contexts: By not studying modern foreign languages, students might have a more limited understanding of global contexts and cultural nuances, which are valuable skills in an increasingly interconnected world.&#10;3. Missed opportunity for cognitive development: Learning a new language has been shown to improve cognitive abilities such as problem-solving, multitasking, and memory. By not offering modern foreign languages, sixth forms might miss out on these benefits for their students.&#10;4. Short-sighted view of skill applicability: The skills gained through the Welsh Baccalaureate, such as teamwork and communication, are indeed valuable in employment. However, this perspective may be short-sighted, as language skills can also be highly relevant in many industries, particularly those with international connections or involving cross-cultural interactions.&#10;5. Loss of cultural understanding and empathy: Studying a foreign language not only teaches students the language itself but also provides them with insights into the culture, history, and traditions of the countries where the language is spoken. By diminishing the focus on modern foreign languages, there may be less emphasis on fostering cultural understanding and empathy among students.&#10;&#10;In summary, prioritizing the Welsh Baccalaureate over modern foreign languages in sixth forms might limit students' exposure to different cultures, cognitive development opportunities, and language skills that are applicable in various employment contexts. It is essential to recognize the value of linguistic and cultural competencies alongside the transferable skills gained through programs like the Welsh Baccalaureate." />
    <node id=", I think what parents and learners are looking for is for the range of options. There are some places in, I would think, some sixth forms now, where certain qualifications may not be offered now because of the need to pick up an extra—Welsh bac. So, for example, modern foreign languages is reducing quite dramatically in Wales, and, I think, I picked up today a few schools had been saying that one of the reasons is, 'We have to put our focus on the Welsh bac to ensure that is achieved rather than giving the opportunity to do the modern foreign language.'&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: But it could be a short-sighted view because what some young people tell us is that at the time—and parents—they didn't really appreciate what skills they were actually learning, and by the time they'd got into employment, that working as a team, the communication skills, they thought, 'Ah, we did—. I know what this is about', and it all makes sense at that point. So, to try and, sort of, discourage it at a younger age may be doing them a disservice in the long run.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM" />
    <node id="1. Regarding the requirement of obtaining a qualification to develop soft skills, Nick Brazil and other speakers suggest that it is not necessary for soft skills to be developed through a formal qualification. They mention programs that their institutions offer which provide opportunities to develop these skills without being a qualification.&#10;2. There is an instance where young people from the Swansea area may be seeking flexibility in the curriculum offered by their institution. Lynne Neagle AM asks Nick Brazil if they have any young people coming to them from the Swansea area who are looking for this flexibility, which may not be available in local schools due to the requirement of participating in the Welsh Baccalaureate.&#10;3. Nick Brazil also highlights that in their college, students doing four A-levels are still required to participate in the Welsh Baccalaureate, but they believe this should be approached with flexibility based on the learner's needs and goals." />
    <node id="1. Debate over skill development: There is debate on whether all the intended skills are being fully realized by learners in the Welsh Baccalaureate, particularly at Level 1 and 2. Some stakeholders argue that not all students develop the desired independent skills due to rushed approaches or inconsistencies in teaching methods." />
    <node id="The primary individuals who inquire about not having to do the Welsh bac are college staff, particularly those working with learners at Level 1 and Level 2. They bring up this issue because many of their students come from schools where the Welsh bac may have been completed in a rushed manner, especially during the last four weeks of term. This results in learners not fully developing the desired independent skills that the program is meant to foster.&#10;&#10;The question about opting out of the Welsh bac is typically asked when learners are transitioning from school to further education at the college level. The college staff want to ensure that the learners' best interests are served, and in some cases, this may mean suggesting that students should not be required to do the Welsh bac if they have already completed it in a less-than-optimal manner in their previous schooling." />
    <node id=" that certain institutions have. So, for example, we had an indication from the union representing Welsh-speaking teachers that if the baccalaureate was universally adopted, it would remove an artificial choice, basically, for learners, i.e. they were losing Welsh-speaking students who didn't want to do the bac to English-speaking institutions. So, I wonder if you could tell me how much the decision in your individual colleges not to offer bac is down to the opportunity that it presents you to attract students, particularly from sixth forms, where students may be obliged to do the bac.&#10;Speaker: Kay Martin&#10;Content: That is not the case, I would say. When a learner comes to us, we—. I'd like to think that all the staff in all the colleges do what is in the best interests of the learner. In some cases, it's to go back to school, and we absolutely say, 'You need to go back to school.' If somebody comes from a Welsh-medium school, then usually I will speak to the head and make sure that we have a programme in place, that either they're studying their programme bilingually or through the medium of Welsh, or that we" />
    <node id=" have interviews in those universities.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: But in terms of Bangor and Glyndŵr University, there's no problem there, though.&#10;Speaker: Dafydd Evans&#10;Content: No, there is no problem there.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Thank you. Right, the next questions are from Julie Morgan.&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: Thank you, Chair. Good morning. I think you've already got into this bit of the discussion, but what are your views on how comparable the Welsh bac is to other qualifications? I don't know if you've got any more comments on that.&#10;Speaker: Dafydd Evans&#10;Content: Well, obviously, as we noted, it's become a very rigorous, very large qualification. Actually, it's probably larger than an A-level by now. And, therefore, regarding the rigour and so forth, that's absolutely fine, but I think one of the problems that you're hearing is that perhaps the Welsh bac is trying to be all things to all men. At one end of the spectrum it's trying to be a rigorous qualification that stands up" />
    <node id=" able to join us. If it's okay with you, we'll go straight into questions, and the first ones are from Siân Gwenllian.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Good morning. I'll be asking my questions in Welsh.&#10;Speaker: Dafydd Evans&#10;Content: Could I start and then open it up? Thank you very much for the opportunity to give evidence. But just to give you the context, I think, if you were asking about the vast majority of subjects what the view of ColegauCymru would be, it would be quite unanimous, but I think on the Welsh bac there is a difference of opinion, and I'm sure you'll hear those differences on the panel before you today. We've possibly chosen this panel because there are differences of opinion. So, I just want to give you that context at the outset. To answer the specific question, no, I don't think that employers have a clear understanding of what the Welsh bac means or what it includes. Personally I don't think that even the title of the Welsh bac is helpful, because it doesn't say what's happening in the tin. So, I" />
    <node id="1. Employers might consider a WorldSkills participant more favorably than a learner who has completed the Welsh Baccalaureate because of the direct industry skills demonstration and practical experience gained through WorldSkills participation. The Welsh Baccalaureate, while designed to develop employability skills, does not offer the same level of hands-on training or recognition in specific technical areas as WorldSkills.&#10;&#10;2. Participating in WorldSkills provides more value to learners and employers compared to the Welsh Baccalaureate due to several factors:&#10;&#10;   a) Global Recognition: WorldSkills is an international platform showcasing skilled professionals, while the Welsh Baccalaureate has limited recognition outside of Wales. This global recognition increases employability and career opportunities for participants.&#10;   &#10;   b) Specialized Skill Development: WorldSkills focuses on specific skill sets, which can be better aligned with industry requirements compared to the broader range of skills covered by the Welsh Baccalaureate. This focus allows participants to demonstrate mastery in their chosen field and showcase relevant expertise to potential employers.&#10;   &#10;   c) Practical Experience: WorldSkills offers learners hands-on experience, working on real-world projects and competing against international peers. The direct practical application of skills can lead to better retention and understanding compared to the more theoretical approach taken by the Welsh Baccalaureate.&#10;   &#10;   d) Stronger Employer Engagement: WorldSkills involves industry leaders in skill development, evaluation, and competition organization, ensuring that training remains relevant and up-to-date with industry demands. This employer engagement leads to better alignment between WorldSkills participants' skills and employer needs.&#10;&#10;In summary, employers might consider a WorldSkills participant more favorably due to the direct industry skills demonstration and practical experience gained through participation. Compared to the Welsh Baccalaureate, WorldSkills offers specialized skill development, practical experience, strong employer engagement, and global recognition, providing more value to learners and employers in terms of career opportunities and relevance to industry needs." />
    <node id="1. Lack of understanding and awareness about the Welsh Baccalaureate: Some employers might not fully comprehend the structure, goals, or benefits of the Welsh Baccalaureate program, which can lead to misconceptions regarding its rigor and value. This lack of understanding may stem from insufficient communication between educators and industry leaders or limited exposure to the program's outcomes.&#10;&#10;2. Perception of bureaucracy and workload: Employers might view the Welsh Baccalaureate as an added burden for learners, fearing that it may detract from their focus on core subjects relevant to specific industries. This perception can negatively influence their view of the program's rigor and value, as they prioritize domain-specific knowledge over cross-curricular skills development.&#10;&#10;3. Misalignment between employer needs and Welsh Baccalaureate objectives: If employers perceive that the Welsh Baccalaureate does not directly address the skill gaps in their workforce, they might undervalue its contribution to developing well-rounded employees. For instance, if employers prioritize hard skills related to STEM fields, they might question the value of a program that focuses on softer and entrepreneurial skills.&#10;&#10;4. Variability in implementation and outcomes: The inconsistencies in teaching methods, models, and learner performance associated with the Welsh Baccalaureate can lead to differing perspectives among employers. Some might have had positive experiences hiring students who have completed the program, while others may not have observed tangible benefits.&#10;&#10;5. Employer buy-in and recognition: When employers understand the Welsh Baccalaureate's objectives, benefits, and alignment with industry requirements, they are more likely to appreciate its value and rigor. This appreciation can translate into a more positive perception of the program and its contribution to developing skilled candidates for employment.&#10;&#10;In summary, varying perspectives among employers regarding the Welsh Baccalaureate's rigor and value can be attributed to factors such as lack of understanding, perception of bureaucracy and workload, misalignment between employer needs and program objectives, variability in implementation and outcomes, and employer buy-in and recognition. Enhancing communication between educators and employers, promoting a clearer understanding of the Welsh Baccalaureate's goals and benefits, and emphasizing its alignment with industry requirements can contribute to more positive perceptions among employers, ultimately enhancing the program's value in preparing students for employment." />
    <node id="1. Learners might choose further education institutions like the one Nick Brazil represents due to the flexibility and diverse range of skill development opportunities they offer. This is suggested by Lynne Neagle AM's question about young people from Swansea seeking more flexible curriculum options, which may not be available in local schools due to participation requirements in the Welsh Baccalaureate.&#10;2. Nick Brazil emphasizes that their institution offers a range of opportunities and makes decisions based on the best interests of each learner. The fact that they offer programs specifically designed for soft skill development without requiring formal qualifications indicates an effort to cater to different student needs and preferences.&#10;3. Sian Gwenllian AM raises the idea that sometimes parents' perceptions, rather than actual benefits for the pupil, guide their decision-making in choosing an education provider. However, Nick Brazil stresses the importance of offering a full range of qualification opportunities while avoiding limiting learners' choices or making certain qualifications compulsory.&#10;&#10;In summary, further education institutions like Nick Brazil's may attract learners seeking more flexibility and diverse skill development opportunities that align with their individual needs and goals. These institutions might provide an alternative to local schools that have rigid curriculum requirements, such as participation in the Welsh Baccalaureate at specific levels." />
    <node id=" the time, but the learners usually—as I said—have sometimes had not the best experience pre 16 and that's why they ask the question straight away.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: Can I suggest that maybe, then, the perception that parents have is steering the way rather than the actual benefits for the pupil in your institution? If you're telling them, 'Come to us, you don't have to actually do it because we know you don't like it', is that the correct way of approaching education?&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: No. Education is about offering the range and offering it correctly.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: I'm being devil's advocate.&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: Yes, I know, I totally understand, but it's about offering the full range of qualification opportunities for learners. If you don't offer the full range, which, sometimes—if you, obviously, limit and you make qualifications compulsory, that can limit the choice of opportunities as well. So, I think what parents and learners are looking for is for the range of options. There are some places in, I would think, some sixth forms now," />
    <node id="1. Soft skills and commercial skills: STEM employers are looking for &quot;softer skills&quot; and &quot;commercial skills&quot; which they consider to be hard skills that are not always provided by professional qualifications. These can include teamwork, communication, problem-solving, and industry knowledge.&#10;&#10;2. Employers' perspective on the Welsh Baccalaureate: While some employers may not fully understand or value the Welsh Baccalaureate as a means of achieving a well-rounded employee, incorporating more employer input in the review of the qualification can help align it with industry requirements and promote relevant skill development. Employer buy-in is crucial for the success of this initiative, as it ensures their understanding and recognition of the Welsh Baccalaureate's value.&#10;&#10;3. Challenges in cultivating skills: There is concern that the rigorous nature of the Welsh Baccalaureate might deter more able and talented STEM students from pursuing four A-levels, as they are an essential part of the sector's workforce. Additionally, there is debate over whether all intended skills are being fully realized by learners in the Welsh Baccalaureate, particularly at Level 1 and 2, due to rushed approaches or inconsistencies in teaching methods.&#10;&#10;In summary, STEM employers are looking for soft skills and commercial skills that can be hard to come by. They believe these skills can be better cultivated in students through closer collaboration between education providers and employers, as well as a clearer understanding of the Welsh Baccalaureate's benefits among employers. Addressing challenges in skill development and learner experiences will also contribute to enhancing the overall effectiveness of the program in preparing students for employment opportunities." />
    <node id="1. In Swansea, all students are required to participate in the Welsh Baccalaureate, regardless of their course of study (A-levels or vocational qualifications).&#10;2. In Cardiff and the Vale, only students who are part of the Seren network are required to participate in the Welsh Baccalaureate.&#10;3. In a particular college mentioned, all students, including those doing four A-levels, must participate in the Welsh Baccalaureate. However, the college aims to implement 'contextualising the curriculum' more broadly, incorporating industry experts and mentorship programs to enhance the learning experience.&#10;4. The policy of universal adoption of the Welsh Baccalaureate seems not to be strictly enforced, as some institutions have moved away from mandatory participation due to changes in the program." />
    <node id=" and the Vale, they do unless they're in the Seren network, and in your college, everybody does it, even if they're doing four A-levels. Do you think that's a satisfactory situation, and are you satisfied with the communication and the guidance and the steer that everyone's getting from Welsh Government on this? Because we're meant to have a policy of universal adoption, but that doesn't really seem to be happening on the ground.&#10;Speaker: Kay Martin&#10;Content: And I think, if you'd asked us a few years ago, we were all heading for universal adoption, but because the Welsh bac has changed into something that isn't 100 per cent what we think it should be, then we've stopped the universal adoption, if you like. So, we are trying to do what's in the best interests of the learner, but I think, as you said, we've mentioned some other programmes, and if we could look at—. We've got industry experts in colleges. We've got industry experts that are brought into colleges as well, some more than others, to bring that to life, if you like. We've got mentorship programmes, we send people out, and we just need to incorporate that better." />
    <node id="1. Employers' understanding of the Welsh Baccalaureate: Based on the transcript, it appears that there is a significant lack of understanding among employers regarding the Welsh Baccalaureate and its benefits. This issue stems from the fact that the program has not been effectively sold to employers, who should ideally be engaged in supporting schools and colleges to deliver it. As Sian Gwenllian AM mentioned, some employers might not fully comprehend the value or objectives of the Welsh Baccalaureate. This lack of understanding is a significant problem, as expressed by multiple speakers in the transcript.&#10;2. Title of the Welsh Baccalaureate: Sian Gwenllian AM raised concerns about the title &quot;Welsh bac&quot; not accurately representing the content and objectives of the program. She proposed that a more descriptive title, such as &quot;skills challenge certificate,&quot; would better convey its purpose and value to employers, parents, and students. This change could help clarify the contents and goals of the Welsh Baccalaureate, potentially increasing understanding and appreciation among various stakeholders, including employers." />
    <node id="1. Prioritizing the Welsh Bac over modern foreign languages in Welsh sixth forms could lead to a significant reduction in students studying these languages, which may limit their language proficiency and cultural understanding. This limitation could negatively impact their future employment opportunities, especially in today's globalized economy where multilingualism is valued.&#10;2. When the Welsh Bac is prioritized over modern foreign languages, students might miss out on developing essential communication skills, intercultural competence, and cognitive benefits associated with learning a second language. These skills are transferable and valuable in various professional settings.&#10;3. Some stakeholders argue that not all intended skills are being fully realized by learners in the Welsh Baccalaureate, particularly at Level 1 and 2. If this is the case, students might not be adequately prepared for further education or employment, as they may lack crucial independent skills.&#10;4. Young people may not immediately appreciate the value of the skills they are learning in the Welsh Baccalaureate, but they often realize their importance later in life, particularly in the context of employment. Soft skills like teamwork and communication become increasingly valuable in the workforce and can contribute to a learner's employability and success.&#10;5. A one-size-fits-all approach may not be beneficial for all learners, as different students have varying needs and interests. For some students, focusing on modern foreign languages might be more advantageous for their future careers, especially if they plan to work in international industries or study abroad.&#10;6. Colleges and universities may place less value on the Welsh Bac, depending on the learner's intended field of study. For example, Janet Finch-Saunders AM mentions that the Welsh Bac may not help health and social care students become more skilled and employable, implying that modern foreign languages or other subjects might be more relevant to their career goals.&#10;7. There is a risk that learners who complete the Welsh Bac in a rushed manner, especially during the last four weeks of term, may not fully develop the desired independent skills. This situation could leave them at a disadvantage compared to students from schools or systems where the program is taught more effectively and consistently throughout their education." />
    <node id="1. The original vision of the Welsh Baccalaureate, as supported by all, was to develop a range of skills in learners that extend beyond academic abilities. This includes &quot;soft skills&quot; and &quot;commercial skills&quot; that are often not provided by professional qualifications but are necessary for success in various industries (point 1).&#10;2. The Welsh Baccalaureate aims to provide challenges and industry exposure for students, particularly those from less academic backgrounds (point 2), which can help them develop the necessary skills for their future careers.&#10;3. The mandatory entrepreneurship and enterprise unit in Spain, as mentioned by Lynne Neagle AM, is seen as a more fit-for-purpose approach when compared to the current Welsh Baccalaureate (point 6). This implies that the Spanish model might align better with the original vision of developing well-rounded students with entrepreneurial skills and industry knowledge.&#10;4. However, there are concerns about the rigorous nature of the Welsh Baccalaureate discouraging more able and talented STEM students from pursuing four A-levels (point 3), which is an essential part of the sector's workforce. Addressing this issue might be necessary for the Welsh Baccalaureate to fulfill its original vision.&#10;5. The lack of understanding among employers about the Welsh Baccalaureate and its benefits, as well as the pressure it puts on learners in terms of bureaucracy and workload, has raised questions about whether it truly develops the skills that employers require (point 4). Ensuring that the qualification is valued by employers would be crucial to achieving its original vision." />
