    <edge source="1. Perception of repetition: The perception among learners that the Welsh Baccalaureate experience in school is repetitive with college coursework can be attributed to the fact that many students have already been exposed to similar content and skills during their Welsh Bac experience at the school level. This redundancy can lead to a lack of motivation and engagement, particularly for students transitioning from Level 1 to Level 2.&#10;&#10;2. Adoption by universities: The adoption of the Welsh Baccalaureate by universities and admissions tutors impacts its value for university applications, especially for competitive programs like dentistry or those offered by Oxbridge or high-level Russell Group universities. Although the Welsh Baccalaureate is technically universally adopted by universities, not all admissions tutors in every university consider it equally valuable. Some may prefer four A-levels over a combination of A-levels and the Welsh Baccalaureate, particularly for subjects like dentistry and those within the Seren network.&#10;&#10;This inconsistency in adoption by universities and admissions tutors can lead to confusion among students regarding the true value of the Welsh Baccalaureate for their university applications, especially when pursuing competitive programs or applying to prestigious institutions." target="It is quite questionable for level 1 and 2 learners to effectively benefit from resitting GCSE exams and adding a Welsh Baccalaureate qualification. The pressure on these students is already high due to their resits in English and maths, and the added volume of work from the Welsh baccalaureate can increase this pressure further. This can be counterproductive, as the primary goal for bringing such learners in at that level should be building their confidence and skills, which might be better served through a more focused curriculum without the additional burden of the Welsh Baccalaureate. Furthermore, there is uncertainty about whether all the intended skills developed through the Welsh baccalaureate are indeed being fully realized by learners. The benefits of the Welsh Baccalaureate may be better experienced at Level 3, once students have built a stronger foundation and academic capacity to handle its demands.">
