    <edge source="1. In Swansea, all students are required to participate in the Welsh Baccalaureate, regardless of whether they are doing A-levels or vocational qualifications.&#10;2. In Cardiff and the Vale, only students who are part of the Seren network (an initiative for encouraging able and talented young people to consider higher education) are required to participate in the Welsh Baccalaureate.&#10;3. In a particular college, all students, including those doing four A-levels, must participate in the Welsh Baccalaureate. This is different from the approach taken in other regions and institutions. The speakers do not explicitly discuss the reasons for these differences in policy, but they suggest that the implementation of 'contextualising the curriculum' may vary depending on the specific challenges and opportunities faced by each institution or region." target="1. Lack of clarity in title: The title &quot;Welsh Baccalaureate&quot; does not clearly convey its purpose or objectives, which can lead to confusion among stakeholders such as employers, parents, and young people. A more descriptive title, like &quot;Skills Challenge Certificate,&quot; might be easier for them to understand and appreciate its value.&#10;&#10;2. Inadequate understanding by employers: There is a perception that many employers do not fully comprehend the objectives or value of the Welsh Baccalaureate. This issue could be more pronounced among small and microbusinesses, as they may have limited resources to stay updated on educational policy developments and changes in Wales.&#10;&#10;3. Size-based disparity in understanding: The challenge in communicating the value and objectives of the Welsh Baccalaureate varies depending on the size of the employer. Larger employers with dedicated HR personnel might be more aware of policy developments and education evolution, while small and microbusinesses are often too focused on their core operations to engage or understand the Welsh Baccalaureate fully.&#10;&#10;4. Limited awareness among parents and young people: The lack of understanding about the Welsh Baccalaureate extends to parents and young people themselves. This can be a significant challenge, as they may not appreciate its benefits in developing essential skills or preparing for higher education or employment opportunities.&#10;&#10;5. Addressing these challenges: To improve communication about the Welsh Baccalaureate's value and objectives, there is a need to adopt more effective marketing strategies that cater specifically to different stakeholder groups. This may involve creating tailored resources for employers, especially small and microbusinesses, as well as providing clearer information for parents and young people. Additionally, it would be helpful if educational institutions regularly engaged with these stakeholders to address their concerns and promote better understanding of the Welsh Baccalaureate's objectives and benefits.">
