    <edge source=" more greatly, which I accept. Are you worried at all, though, that some of the more able and talented STEM students, in particular—who are needed in your sector, after all—might be deterred from doing those four A-levels because of the bac, because, presumably, you need a mix of these talents? You talked about the more able and talented vocational learners, but also you have more able and talented academic learners—presumably you need them all.&#10;Speaker: Ed Evans&#10;Content: We do. There's a big range, and some really high achievers coming into the sector as well. So, it is about that mix. I think the discussion that I've had with our employers has been around the academic side of things, if you like. The qualifications are well catered for. So, it's almost a given somebody's been through that route. What isn't there is some of those softer skills, but also some—. I was almost going to call commercial skills 'soft' there—.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Call them 'commercial'.&#10;Speaker: Ed Evans&#10;Content: Commercial skills are hard skills, which are very, very difficult to come by. So, the" target="1. Some employers in the sector find that STEM students lack &quot;softer skills&quot; and &quot;commercial skills,&quot; which they consider to be hard skills. These skills are not always provided by professional qualifications and are necessary for success in the industry.&#10;2. The Welsh Baccalaureate is seen as a way to develop these skills, particularly for students who come from a less academic background. It provides challenges that test their abilities and exposes them to industry knowledge.&#10;3. There is concern that the rigorous nature of the Welsh Baccalaureate might deter more able and talented STEM students from pursuing four A-levels, as they are an essential part of the sector's workforce.&#10;4. The lack of understanding among employers about the Welsh Baccalaureate and its benefits, along with the pressure it puts