ion, it appears that Dafydd Evans is primarily responsible for making efforts to persuade employers of the Welsh Baccalaureate's worthiness. However, collective action from various stakeholders, including educators, policymakers, and industry leaders, can contribute significantly to enhancing employers' understanding and appreciation of the program." target="1. Dafydd Evans believes that incorporating more employer input in the review of the Welsh Baccalaureate qualification can help improve its focus on employability and entrepreneurial skills. He suggests this be done by giving employers a sense of ownership in the creation and design of the qualification, which would lead to better alignment with industry requirements and promote relevant skill development. Employer buy-in is crucial for the success of this initiative, as it ensures their understanding and recognition of the Welsh Baccalaureate's value.&#10;&#10;2. Dafydd Evans also recommends involving employers in the review process of the Welsh Baccalaureate to emphasize employability and entrepreneurial skills within the program. Strengthening the relationship between schools, colleges, and local businesses can help bridge the gap in understanding through workshops, job fairs, or internship programs. Tailoring the Welsh Baccalaureate curriculum to meet industry requirements, creating resources and materials explaining its benefits, and encouraging industry leaders to advocate for the program can also contribute significantly to enhancing employers' understanding and appreciation of the program.&#10;&#10;3. Dafydd Evans acknowledges that there have been negative experiences with the Welsh Baccalaureate, particularly among level 1 and 2 learners who may already be struggling with English and maths resits. He suggests that a more focused curriculum without the additional burden of the Welsh Baccalaureate might better serve these students at lower levels, while reserving its benefits for those at Level 3 with stronger academic foundations.">
