    <edge source="1. Some employers in the sector find that STEM students lack &quot;softer skills&quot; and &quot;commercial skills,&quot; which they consider to be hard skills. These skills are not always provided by professional qualifications and are necessary for success in the industry.&#10;2. The Welsh Baccalaureate is seen as a way to develop these skills, particularly for students who come from a less academic background. It provides challenges that test their abilities and exposes them to industry knowledge.&#10;3. There is concern that the rigorous nature of the Welsh Baccalaureate might deter more able and talented STEM students from pursuing four A-levels, as they are an essential part of the sector's workforce.&#10;4. The lack of understanding among employers about the Welsh Baccalaureate and its benefits, along with the pressure it puts on learners in terms of bureaucracy and workload, has raised questions about whether it truly develops the skills that employers require.&#10;5. Employers prioritize the main qualifications relevant to their industry, such as engineering qualifications for engineers. While they want well-rounded employees, they might not fully understand or value the Welsh Baccalaureate as a means of achieving this goal." target="1. Dafydd Evans believes that incorporating more employer input in the review of the Welsh Baccalaureate qualification can help improve its focus on employability and entrepreneurial skills. He suggests this be done by giving employers a sense of ownership in the creation and design of the qualification, which would lead to better alignment with industry requirements and promote relevant skill development. Employer buy-in is crucial for the success of this initiative, as it ensures their understanding and recognition of the Welsh Baccalaureate's value.&#10;&#10;2. Dafydd Evans also recommends involving employers in the review process of the Welsh Baccalaureate to emphasize employability and entrepreneurial skills within the program. Strengthening the relationship between schools, colleges, and local businesses can help bridge the gap in understanding through workshops, job fairs, or internship programs. Tailoring the Welsh Baccalaureate curriculum to meet industry requirements, creating resources and materials explaining its benefits, and encouraging industry leaders to advocate for the program can also contribute significantly to enhancing employers' understanding and appreciation of the program.&#10;&#10;3. Dafydd Evans acknowledges that there have been negative experiences with the Welsh Baccalaureate, particularly among level 1 and 2 learners who may already be struggling with English and maths resits. He suggests that a more focused curriculum without the additional burden of the Welsh Baccalaureate might better serve these students at lower levels, while reserving its benefits for those at Level 3 with stronger academic foundations.">
