wn to improve cognitive abilities such as problem-solving, multitasking, and memory. By not offering modern foreign languages, sixth forms might miss out on these benefits for their students.&#10;4. Short-sighted view of skill applicability: The skills gained through the Welsh Baccalaureate, such as teamwork and communication, are indeed valuable in employment. However, this perspective may be short-sighted, as language skills can also be highly relevant in many industries, particularly those with international connections or involving cross-cultural interactions.&#10;5. Loss of cultural understanding and empathy: Studying a foreign language not only teaches students the language itself but also provides them with insights into the culture, history, and traditions of the countries where the language is spoken. By diminishing the focus on modern foreign languages, there may be less emphasis on fostering cultural understanding and empathy among students.&#10;&#10;In summary, prioritizing the Welsh Baccalaureate over modern foreign languages in sixth forms might limit students' exposure to different cultures, cognitive development opportunities, and language skills that are applicable in various employment contexts. It is essential to recognize the value of linguistic and cultural competencies alongside the transferable skills gained through programs like the Welsh Baccalaureate.">
