    <edge source=" who have come through from a less academic background, the Welsh bac gives them that ability, I guess, not to pursue so much of an academic focus, but to test them in terms of the challenges, but also, to—. And I think if it was working properly and we did have employers engaged in this, and supporting schools and colleges to deliver it, they would actually be learning a lot more directly from industry. And some children, some pupils, some young people, they respond far, far better to that. And I think that's the issue for me—that we've not really sold this to employers to actually engage with them. All of my understanding of this is literally as a parent, and that would be true of a lot of employers as well. So, perhaps there are differences across the sector, but I think, certainly for my sector, we would really value the growth of the Welsh baccalaureate.&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: What are we going to do, then, to improve employers' understanding of the Welsh bac, and whose work is it to try to persuade employers that it is worth while, if you feel that it is worth while, of course?&#10;" target="1. Employers' understanding of the Welsh Baccalaureate: Based on the transcript, it appears that there is a significant lack of understanding among employers regarding the Welsh Baccalaureate and its benefits. This issue stems from the fact that the program has not been effectively sold to employers, who should ideally be engaged in supporting schools and colleges to deliver it. As Sian Gwenllian AM mentioned, some employers might not fully comprehend the value or objectives of the Welsh Baccalaureate. This lack of understanding is a significant problem, as expressed by multiple speakers in the transcript.&#10;2. Title of the Welsh Baccalaureate: Sian Gwenllian AM raised concerns about the title &quot;Welsh bac&quot; not accurately representing the content and objectives of the program. She proposed that a more descriptive title, such as &quot;skills challenge certificate,&quot; would better convey its purpose and value to employers, parents, and students. This change could help clarify the contents and goals of the Welsh Baccalaureate, potentially increasing understanding and appreciation among various stakeholders, including employers.">
