    <edge source="The Welsh Baccalaureate (Welsh bac) is being undermined by some schools completing it in the last four weeks of term. This rushed approach results in learners not fully developing the desired independent skills, which defeats the purpose of the program. The perceived value of the Welsh bac is also affected by the variable models and approaches to teaching it, leading to inconsistencies in skill development. Some schools prioritize the Welsh bac as a requirement for admission, but its value depends on the institution and subjects being studied. There are concerns that not all intended skills developed through the Welsh bac are being fully realized by learners, particularly at Level 1 and 2 where the primary goal should be building confidence and skills with a more focused curriculum. However, there is evidence that when taught effectively, the Welsh bac can be beneficial and rewarding for learners, helping them develop valuable skills. The interviewees seem to agree that a more consistent approach to teaching the Welsh bac is needed to ensure its value and effectiveness in developing independent skills among learners." target=" that in some schools, and I'm not saying all, doing the bac is something that everybody does in the last four weeks of term, and that undermines the whole idea of the bac anyway. It's just not fair on the learners or the people teaching the bac. Is that a fair observation?&#10;Speaker: Dr Rachel Bowen&#10;Content: I think it's perfectly possible for learners to reach FE college having attained the Welsh bac under the process that you've described, and without necessarily having gone through the holistic inquiry-based independent skills that we would want to see.&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: Yes, and at interview process or during an interview, or in the first week, you can see that they haven't developed those skills, and I think it is down to the variable models that have been put in place. There are lots of different models, and if you put, as I said, the model that you've described in place, there is no way, in that period of time, you're going to develop those skills. But that indicates, again, the value that people are putting on the qualification, if they are squeezing it into three or four weeks of term.&#10;Speaker: Suzy">
