    <edge source="1. Dafydd Evans believes that incorporating more employer input in the review of the Welsh Baccalaureate qualification can help improve its focus on employability and entrepreneurial skills. He suggests this be done by giving employers a sense of ownership in the creation and design of the qualification, which would lead to better alignment with industry requirements and promote relevant skill development. Employer buy-in is crucial for the success of this initiative, as it ensures their understanding and recognition of the Welsh Baccalaureate's value.&#10;&#10;2. Dafydd Evans also recommends involving employers in the review process of the Welsh Baccalaureate to emphasize employability and entrepreneurial skills within the program. Strengthening the relationship between schools, colleges, and local businesses can help bridge the gap in understanding through workshops, job fairs, or internship programs. Tailoring the Welsh Baccalaureate curriculum to meet industry requirements, creating resources and materials explaining its benefits, and encouraging industry leaders to advocate for the program can also contribute significantly to enhancing employers' understanding and appreciation of the program.&#10;&#10;3. Dafydd Evans acknowledges that there have been negative experiences with the Welsh Baccalaureate, particularly among level 1 and 2 learners who may already be struggling with English and maths resits. He suggests that a more focused curriculum without the additional burden of the Welsh Baccalaureate might better serve these students at lower levels, while reserving its benefits for those at Level 3 with stronger academic foundations." target="1. Employers might consider a WorldSkills participant more favorably than a learner who has completed the Welsh Baccalaureate because of the direct industry skills demonstration and practical experience gained through WorldSkills participation. The Welsh Baccalaureate, while designed to develop employability skills, does not offer the same level of hands-on training or recognition in specific technical areas as WorldSkills.&#10;&#10;2. Participating in WorldSkills provides more value to learners and employers compared to the Welsh Baccalaureate due to several factors:&#10;&#10;   a) Global Recognition: WorldSkills is an international platform showcasing skilled professionals, while the Welsh Baccalaureate has limited recognition outside of Wales. This global recognition increases employability and career opportunities for participants.&#10;   &#10;   b) Specialized Skill Development: WorldSkills focuses on specific skill sets, which can be better aligned with industry requirements compared to the broader range of skills covered by the Welsh Baccalaureate. This focus allows participants to demonstrate mastery in their chosen field and showcase relevant expertise to potential employers.&#10;   &#10;   c) Practical Experience: WorldSkills offers learners hands-on experience, working on real-world projects and competing against international peers. The direct practical application of skills can lead to better retention and understanding compared to the more theoretical approach taken by the Welsh Baccalaureate.&#10;   &#10;   d) Stronger Employer Engagement: WorldSkills involves industry leaders in skill development, evaluation, and competition organization, ensuring that training remains relevant and up-to-date with industry demands. This employer engagement leads to better alignment between WorldSkills participants' skills and employer needs.&#10;&#10;In summary, employers might consider a WorldSkills participant more favorably due to the direct industry skills demonstration and practical experience gained through participation. Compared to the Welsh Baccalaureate, WorldSkills offers specialized skill development, practical experience, strong employer engagement, and global recognition, providing more value to learners and employers in terms of career opportunities and relevance to industry needs.">
