    <edge source="1. Dafydd Evans believes that incorporating more employer input in the review of the Welsh Baccalaureate qualification can help improve its focus on employability and entrepreneurial skills. He suggests this be done by giving employers a sense of ownership in the creation and design of the qualification, which would lead to better alignment with industry requirements and promote relevant skill development. Employer buy-in is crucial for the success of this initiative, as it ensures their understanding and recognition of the Welsh Baccalaureate's value.&#10;&#10;2. Dafydd Evans also recommends involving employers in the review process of the Welsh Baccalaureate to emphasize employability and entrepreneurial skills within the program. Strengthening the relationship between schools, colleges, and local businesses can help bridge the gap in understanding through workshops, job fairs, or internship programs. Tailoring the Welsh Baccalaureate curriculum to meet industry requirements, creating resources and materials explaining its benefits, and encouraging industry leaders to advocate for the program can also contribute significantly to enhancing employers' understanding and appreciation of the program.&#10;&#10;3. Dafydd Evans acknowledges that there have been negative experiences with the Welsh Baccalaureate, particularly among level 1 and 2 learners who may already be struggling with English and maths resits. He suggests that a more focused curriculum without the additional burden of the Welsh Baccalaureate might better serve these students at lower levels, while reserving its benefits for those at Level 3 with stronger academic foundations." target="1. Soft skills and commercial skills: STEM employers are looking for &quot;softer skills&quot; and &quot;commercial skills&quot; which they consider to be hard skills that are not always provided by professional qualifications. These can include teamwork, communication, problem-solving, and industry knowledge.&#10;&#10;2. Employers' perspective on the Welsh Baccalaureate: While some employers may not fully understand or value the Welsh Baccalaureate as a means of achieving a well-rounded employee, incorporating more employer input in the review of the qualification can help align it with industry requirements and promote relevant skill development. Employer buy-in is crucial for the success of this initiative, as it ensures their understanding and recognition of the Welsh Baccalaureate's value.&#10;&#10;3. Challenges in cultivating skills: There is concern that the rigorous nature of the Welsh Baccalaureate might deter more able and talented STEM students from pursuing four A-levels, as they are an essential part of the sector's workforce. Additionally, there is debate over whether all intended skills are being fully realized by learners in the Welsh Baccalaureate, particularly at Level 1 and 2, due to rushed approaches or inconsistencies in teaching methods.&#10;&#10;In summary, STEM employers are looking for soft skills and commercial skills that can be hard to come by. They believe these skills can be better cultivated in students through closer collaboration between education providers and employers, as well as a clearer understanding of the Welsh Baccalaureate's benefits among employers. Addressing challenges in skill development and learner experiences will also contribute to enhancing the overall effectiveness of the program in preparing students for employment opportunities.">
