    <edge source="1. Debate over skill development: There is debate on whether all the intended skills are being fully realized by learners in the Welsh Baccalaureate, particularly at Level 1 and 2. Some stakeholders argue that not all students develop the desired independent skills due to rushed approaches or inconsistencies in teaching methods." target="1. Employers might consider a WorldSkills participant more favorably than a learner who has completed the Welsh Baccalaureate because of the direct industry skills demonstration and practical experience gained through WorldSkills participation. The Welsh Baccalaureate, while designed to develop employability skills, does not offer the same level of hands-on training or recognition in specific technical areas as WorldSkills.&#10;&#10;2. Participating in WorldSkills provides more value to learners and employers compared to the Welsh Baccalaureate due to several factors:&#10;&#10;   a) Global Recognition: WorldSkills is an international platform showcasing skilled professionals, while the Welsh Baccalaureate has limited recognition outside of Wales. This global recognition increases employability and career opportunities for participants.&#10;   &#10;   b) Specialized Skill Development: WorldSkills focuses on specific skill sets, which can be better aligned with industry requirements compared to the broader range of skills covered by the Welsh Baccalaureate. This focus allows participants to demonstrate mastery in their chosen field and showcase relevant expertise to potential employers.&#10;   &#10;   c) Practical Experience: WorldSkills offers learners hands-on experience, working on real-world projects and competing against international peers. The direct practical application of skills can lead to better retention and understanding compared to the more theoretical approach taken by the Welsh Baccalaureate.&#10;   &#10;   d) Stronger Employer Engagement: WorldSkills involves industry leaders in skill development, evaluation, and competition organization, ensuring that training remains relevant and up-to-date with industry demands. This employer engagement leads to better alignment between WorldSkills participants' skills and employer needs.&#10;&#10;In summary, employers might consider a WorldSkills participant more favorably due to the direct industry skills demonstration and practical experience gained through participation. Compared to the Welsh Baccalaureate, WorldSkills offers specialized skill development, practical experience, strong employer engagement, and global recognition, providing more value to learners and employers in terms of career opportunities and relevance to industry needs.">
