    <edge source="1. Debate over skill development: There is debate on whether all the intended skills are being fully realized by learners in the Welsh Baccalaureate, particularly at Level 1 and 2. Some stakeholders argue that not all students develop the desired independent skills due to rushed approaches or inconsistencies in teaching methods." target="1. The original vision of the Welsh Baccalaureate, as supported by all, was to develop a range of skills in learners that extend beyond academic abilities. This includes &quot;soft skills&quot; and &quot;commercial skills&quot; that are often not provided by professional qualifications but are necessary for success in various industries (point 1).&#10;2. The Welsh Baccalaureate aims to provide challenges and industry exposure for students, particularly those from less academic backgrounds (point 2), which can help them develop the necessary skills for their future careers.&#10;3. The mandatory entrepreneurship and enterprise unit in Spain, as mentioned by Lynne Neagle AM, is seen as a more fit-for-purpose approach when compared to the current Welsh Baccalaureate (point 6). This implies that the Spanish model might align better with the original vision of developing well-rounded students with entrepreneurial skills and industry knowledge.&#10;4. However, there are concerns about the rigorous nature of the Welsh Baccalaureate discouraging more able and talented STEM students from pursuing four A-levels (point 3), which is an essential part of the sector's workforce. Addressing this issue might be necessary for the Welsh Baccalaureate to fulfill its original vision.&#10;5. The lack of understanding among employers about the Welsh Baccalaureate and its benefits, as well as the pressure it puts on learners in terms of bureaucracy and workload, has raised questions about whether it truly develops the skills that employers require (point 4). Ensuring that the qualification is valued by employers would be crucial to achieving its original vision.">
