    <edge source="1. Soft skills and commercial skills: STEM employers are looking for &quot;softer skills&quot; and &quot;commercial skills&quot; which they consider to be hard skills that are not always provided by professional qualifications. These can include teamwork, communication, problem-solving, and industry knowledge.&#10;&#10;2. Employers' perspective on the Welsh Baccalaureate: While some employers may not fully understand or value the Welsh Baccalaureate as a means of achieving a well-rounded employee, incorporating more employer input in the review of the qualification can help align it with industry requirements and promote relevant skill development. Employer buy-in is crucial for the success of this initiative, as it ensures their understanding and recognition of the Welsh Baccalaureate's value.&#10;&#10;3. Challenges in cultivating skills: There is concern that the rigorous nature of the Welsh Baccalaureate might deter more able and talented STEM students from pursuing four A-levels, as they are an essential part of the sector's workforce. Additionally, there is debate over whether all intended skills are being fully realized by learners in the Welsh Baccalaureate, particularly at Level 1 and 2, due to rushed approaches or inconsistencies in teaching methods.&#10;&#10;In summary, STEM employers are looking for soft skills and commercial skills that can be hard to come by. They believe these skills can be better cultivated in students through closer collaboration between education providers and employers, as well as a clearer understanding of the Welsh Baccalaureate's benefits among employers. Addressing challenges in skill development and learner experiences will also contribute to enhancing the overall effectiveness of the program in preparing students for employment opportunities." target="1. Creating a more structured process for connecting employers with schools through contractual clauses can be achieved by integrating employer involvement into the education system's legal framework. This could include:&#10;   - Developing formal contracts between businesses, schools, and colleges that outline expectations and commitments from both parties.&#10;   - Including clauses in existing business contracts requiring them to engage with local educational institutions, providing mentorships or internships for students.&#10;   - Establishing partnership agreements between employers, schools, and policymakers to ensure a coordinated effort in promoting the Welsh Baccalaureate and its benefits.&#10;&#10;2. Programs like Career Ready play an essential role in effectively engaging employers while providing students with valuable mentorships and internship experiences. These programs:&#10;   - Offer structured, long-term mentoring relationships between industry professionals and students, ensuring consistent support and guidance throughout the program.&#10;   - Provide opportunities for extended work experience through multi-week internships, allowing students to gain practical skills and demonstrate their capabilities to potential employers.&#10;   - Foster higher aspirations among students by exposing them to real-world work environments and helping them build professional networks.&#10;&#10;By combining formalized contractual clauses with successful programs like Career Ready, it is possible to create a more structured and effective process for connecting employers with schools, ultimately enhancing employer understanding of the Welsh Baccalaureate and its benefits while providing students with valuable learning opportunities.">
