    <edge source="1. In Swansea, all students are required to participate in the Welsh Baccalaureate, regardless of their course of study (A-levels or vocational qualifications).&#10;2. In Cardiff and the Vale, only students who are part of the Seren network are required to participate in the Welsh Baccalaureate.&#10;3. In a particular college mentioned, all students, including those doing four A-levels, must participate in the Welsh Baccalaureate. However, the college aims to implement 'contextualising the curriculum' more broadly, incorporating industry experts and mentorship programs to enhance the learning experience.&#10;4. The policy of universal adoption of the Welsh Baccalaureate seems not to be strictly enforced, as some institutions have moved away from mandatory participation due to changes in the program." target=" and the Vale, they do unless they're in the Seren network, and in your college, everybody does it, even if they're doing four A-levels. Do you think that's a satisfactory situation, and are you satisfied with the communication and the guidance and the steer that everyone's getting from Welsh Government on this? Because we're meant to have a policy of universal adoption, but that doesn't really seem to be happening on the ground.&#10;Speaker: Kay Martin&#10;Content: And I think, if you'd asked us a few years ago, we were all heading for universal adoption, but because the Welsh bac has changed into something that isn't 100 per cent what we think it should be, then we've stopped the universal adoption, if you like. So, we are trying to do what's in the best interests of the learner, but I think, as you said, we've mentioned some other programmes, and if we could look at—. We've got industry experts in colleges. We've got industry experts that are brought into colleges as well, some more than others, to bring that to life, if you like. We've got mentorship programmes, we send people out, and we just need to incorporate that better.">
