    <edge source="1. The original vision of the Welsh Baccalaureate, as supported by all, was to develop a range of skills in learners that extend beyond academic abilities. This includes &quot;soft skills&quot; and &quot;commercial skills&quot; that are often not provided by professional qualifications but are necessary for success in various industries (point 1).&#10;2. The Welsh Baccalaureate aims to provide challenges and industry exposure for students, particularly those from less academic backgrounds (point 2), which can help them develop the necessary skills for their future careers.&#10;3. The mandatory entrepreneurship and enterprise unit in Spain, as mentioned by Lynne Neagle AM, is seen as a more fit-for-purpose approach when compared to the current Welsh Baccalaureate (point 6). This implies that the Spanish model might align better with the original vision of developing well-rounded students with entrepreneurial skills and industry knowledge.&#10;4. However, there are concerns about the rigorous nature of the Welsh Baccalaureate discouraging more able and talented STEM students from pursuing four A-levels (point 3), which is an essential part of the sector's workforce. Addressing this issue might be necessary for the Welsh Baccalaureate to fulfill its original vision.&#10;5. The lack of understanding among employers about the Welsh Baccalaureate and its benefits, as well as the pressure it puts on learners in terms of bureaucracy and workload, has raised questions about whether it truly develops the skills that employers require (point 4). Ensuring that the qualification is valued by employers would be crucial to achieving its original vision." target=", to bring that to life, if you like. We've got mentorship programmes, we send people out, and we just need to incorporate that better. We need to spend less time in checking what they've done on assessment and more time in the doing, and the experiential learning that they need to do, rather than it being too much of a paper exercise. By the time you've done all the paperwork you haven't got time to do any of the learning.&#10;Speaker: Nick Brazil&#10;Content: I think, just to support Kay, we're going to need to go back to the original vision of the Welsh bac, which all of us would buy into 100 per cent. I think that has been lost as the qualification's developed over time, and, ultimately, I think all of us would like to see it go back to that to provide those skills that Ed has brought up and everything. I think we all support that. But is it quite right? I'm not sure at the moment.&#10;Speaker: Dafydd Evans&#10;Content: I'll agree. We visited Spain recently, and there they have an entrepreneurship and enterprise unit that is mandatory for everybody, but it appeared to be far more fit for purpose than the">
