    <edge source="1. The Welsh Baccalaureate (Welsh Bac) faces challenges in being a successful rigorous academic qualification that meets university expectations while also developing soft skills and employment readiness in vocational students. There are concerns about the rushed approaches or inconsistencies in teaching methods, which may not allow all intended skills to be fully realized by learners, particularly at Level 1 and 2. Moreover, its rigorous nature might deter more able and talented STEM students from pursuing four A-levels, an essential part of the sector's workforce." target="Based on the provided information, it appears that there is some uncertainty and inconsistency in how Russell Group universities understand and value the Welsh Baccalaureate. While the Welsh Baccalaureate is technically adopted by all universities, including those in the Russell Group, not all admissions tutors within these institutions may equally appreciate its merits, particularly for competitive programs like dentistry or subjects within the Seren network.&#10;&#10;Some learners have reported experiencing a perception that Russell Group universities do not fully comprehend or esteem the Welsh Baccalaureate as highly as other qualifications, such as four A-levels. This discrepancy in adoption can lead to confusion among students about the true value of the Welsh Baccalaureate for their university applications, especially when pursuing competitive programs or applying to prestigious institutions.&#10;&#10;In summary, it seems that while universities, including some Russell Group members, have adopted the Welsh Baccalaureate, there are variations in how thoroughly and genuinely this qualification is valued by admissions tutors across different competitive programs and institutions, leading to potential confusion for learners transitioning from FE colleges.">
