    <edge source="1) The reason some colleges do not require A-level students to take the Welsh Baccalaureate might be due to variations in implementing 'contextualising the curriculum' based on each institution or region's specific challenges and opportunities. This flexibility allows colleges to adapt their programs to meet the diverse needs of their learners better." target="1) The perception among learners that the Welsh Baccalaureate experience in school is repetitive with college coursework can be attributed to the fact that many students have already been exposed to similar content and skills during their Welsh Bac experience at the school level. This redundancy can lead to a lack of motivation and engagement, particularly for students transitioning from Level 1 to Level 2.&#10;&#10;2) The adoption of the Welsh Baccalaureate by universities and admissions tutors impacts its value for university applications, especially for competitive programs like dentistry or those offered by Oxbridge or high-level Russell Group universities. Although the Welsh Baccalaureate is technically universally adopted by universities, not all admissions tutors in every university consider it equally valuable. Some may prefer four A-levels over a combination of A-levels and the Welsh Baccalaureate, particularly for subjects like dentistry and those within the Seren network. This inconsistency can lead to confusion among students regarding the true value of the Welsh Baccalaureate for their university applications, especially when pursuing competitive programs or applying to prestigious institutions.&#10;&#10;For A-level students and Seren network students, this inconsistent adoption may result in an undervaluation of their Welsh Baccalaureate qualification by certain admissions tutors. Since some universities might not view the Welsh Baccalaureate as equally important as four A-levels or specific subject combinations, these students could face challenges when applying to competitive programs or prestigious institutions. It is essential for students and educators to understand these inconsistencies to make informed decisions about the value of pursuing the Welsh Baccalaureate alongside A-levels or other qualifications.">
